[{"id":"VR873045","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">In Experiment <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span>, students are asked to determine an experimental value for Wien’s constant, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"b\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"b\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>b</mi></math></span></span>, which appears in the equation for Wien’s law: <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda sub max equals, the fraction b over T\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"lambda sub max equals, the fraction b over T\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>λ</mi><mi>max</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>b</mi><mi>T</mi></mfrac></math></span></span>. The students have access to a bulb that approximates the spectral output of a blackbody and a sensor that can record the intensity of the light emitted by the bulb as a function of wavelength. The temperature of the bulb can be varied, and the students have access to a sensor that can measure the temperature of the bulb.</p>\n&nbsp;\n\n<div class=\"item_part part_id:A part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"A\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\"><strong>Part A</strong></p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\" style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">i. <strong>Indicate </strong>the quantities that could be measured by the students that would allow them to determine&nbsp;\\(b\\)&nbsp;using a linear graph.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\" style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">ii. Briefly <strong>describe </strong>a method to reduce experimental uncertainty for the measured quantities.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"item_part part_id:B part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"B\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\"><strong>Part B</strong></p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\" style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span id=\"cke_bm_5377S\" style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span>i.&nbsp;<strong>Indicate </strong>what quantities the students could graph on the horizontal and vertical axes to create a linear graph that can be used to determine \\(b\\).&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\" style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">ii. Briefly describe the relationship between&nbsp;\\(b\\)&nbsp;and a feature of the graph from part B i. Your answer may include an equation that relates&nbsp;\\(b\\)&nbsp;and a chosen feature of the graph.&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>The following information applies to parts C and D.</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"item_part part_id:Ci part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"Ci\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows two parallel metal plates enclosed in a vacuum chamber. Each metal plate is connected to a horizontal wire segment that extends to the left and to the right of the vacuum chamber respectively.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR873045.g03.svg\" /></div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">In Experiment <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>, the students have a glass vacuum chamber with two parallel metal plates inside, as shown. The students are asked to use the setup to determine the work function of the metal plates. In each trial, the students use a monochromatic light source with wavelength <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"lambda\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>λ</mi></math></span></span> to shine light on one of the plates. Once current is detected, the students increase the potential difference <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta V\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"delta V\" overflow=\"scroll\"> <mtext>Δ</mtext> <mi>V</mi> </math></span></span> of the power supply until the ammeter reads zero. In each trial, the students adjust the light source to a different wavelength <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"lambda\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>λ</mi></math></span></span>. They collect the following data show in&nbsp; Table 1 on the wavelengths of the incident light and the potential difference from the power supply when the current stops.</p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph text-center\"><strong>Table 1</strong></p>\n\n<div class=\"table_wrapper\">\n<table class=\"tgroup align:center cols:4\">\n\t<colgroup>\n\t\t<col class=\"colspec colname:col1 colnum:1 colwidth:100\" />\n\t\t<col class=\"colspec colname:col2 colnum:2 colwidth:100\" />\n\t\t<col class=\"colspec colname:col3 colnum:3 colwidth:100\" />\n\t\t<col class=\"colspec colname:col4 colnum:4 colwidth:100\" />\n\t</colgroup>\n\t<tbody class=\"tbody\">\n\t\t<tr class=\"row\">\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col2\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lambda in nanometers\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"lambda in nanometers\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>λ</mi><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mtext>nm</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></math></span></span></td>\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col3\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta V in volts\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"delta V in volts\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Δ</mtext><mi>V</mi><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mtext>V</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></math></span></span></td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr class=\"row\">\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col2\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"450\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"450\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>450</mn></math></span></span></td>\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col3\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"0.45\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"0.45\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>0.45</mn></math></span></span></td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr class=\"row\">\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col2\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"350\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"350\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>350</mn></math></span></span></td>\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col3\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1.25\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"1.25\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1.25</mn></math></span></span></td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr class=\"row\">\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col2\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"250\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"250\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>250</mn></math></span></span></td>\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col3\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2.65\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"2.65\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2.65</mn></math></span></span></td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr class=\"row\">\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col2\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"150\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"150\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>150</mn></math></span></span></td>\n\t\t\t<td class=\"entry colname:col3\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"6.00\" role=\"math\"><math alttext=\"6.00\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>6.00</mn></math></span></span></td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"item_part part_id:C part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"C\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\"><strong>Part C</strong></p>\n\n<ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\">\n\t<li class=\"list_item\">\n\t<p class=\"list_paragraph\">i.&nbsp;<strong>Label</strong>&nbsp;the axes of the grid provided with measured or calculated quantities. Include units, as appropriate. The graphed quantities should yield a linear graph that can be used to determine the work function of the metal.</p>\n\t</li>\n\t<li class=\"list_item\">\n\t<p class=\"list_paragraph\">ii. On the grid, create a graph of the quantities indicated in part C i.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li class=\"list_item\">\n\t\t<p class=\"list_paragraph\"><strong style=\"font-style: inherit; font-variant-ligatures: inherit; font-variant-caps: inherit;\">Label</strong><span style=\"font-style: inherit; font-variant-ligatures: inherit; font-variant-caps: inherit; font-weight: inherit;\">&nbsp;the vertical and horizontal axes with numerical scales.</span></p>\n\t\t</li>\n\t\t<li class=\"list_item\">\n\t\t<p class=\"list_paragraph\"><strong>Plot</strong>&nbsp;the corresponding data points on the grid.</p>\n\t\t</li>\n\t\t<li class=\"list_item\">\n\t\t<p class=\"list_paragraph\">Table 2 is provided in your booklet for scratch work, but the table will not be scored.</p>\n\t\t</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p class=\"list_paragraph text-center\"><img alt=\"A blank 30 by 30 grid. The left side and bottom side each include blank lines for Quantity and (units, if appropriate).\" height=\"425\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/f75888b8-a6de-4288-9408-1108002624ae.png\" width=\"596\" /></p>\n\n<ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\">\n\t<li class=\"list_item\">\n\t<p class=\"list_paragraph\">&nbsp;</p>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\">&nbsp;</div>\n\n<ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\">\n\t<li class=\"list_item\">\n\t<p class=\"list_paragraph\">iii. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Draw</span> the best-fit line for the data graphed in part C ii.</p>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"item_part part_id:D part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"D\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\"><strong>Part D</strong></p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Using the best-fit line, <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">calculate</span> an experimental value for the work function of the metal.</p>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR873045_rubric"}]